<div>
  <p class="text-center" style="font-size: 19px;height: 54px;">10 Best Bachelor of Insurance & Risk Management Degree
    Programs</p>
  <p>There are currently somewhere between 50 and 70 RMI programs available in the United States, depending on whether
    one includes certificates and minors in their tally. But we weren’t looking for just any programs when we compiled
    our list; we wanted the best, which to us meant finding the schools with the most focused, comprehensive options
    for students who want to immerse themselves completely in this uniquely specialized field. Therefore, we did not
    consider BBA or BSBA degrees (which typically consist mainly of business courses with a relatively small number of
    RMI classes) or online programs.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Dedicated Department: the schools with the largest and most complete RMI programs often dedicate an entire
      department to the subject. On the other hand, it’s more common for colleges with smaller, less significant
      programs to lump them into their business or finance department.</li>
    <li>Specializations: one key sign that a program’s curriculum has become truly comprehensive is when it starts
      branching into specializations. Schools with so many RMI classes available that they can offer multiple
      variations of the same degree are more likely to appeal to students, too.</li>
    <li>Advanced Program: colleges that have developed their programs to the point that they are attracting graduate
      students – and have faculty engaged in RMI research – send a signal about their dedication to the topic. In
      addition, schools that have achieved this status may be more likely to offer research/experiential learning
      opportunities to undergrads.</li>
    <li>Productivity: the number of RMI degrees that an institution confers in a given year provides an indication of
      how “productive” that program is; larger numbers means more students choosing – and sticking with – the RMI
      major. (This data came from both school websites and College Navigator.)</li>
    <li>Actuarial Excellence: although technically different disciplines, there is significant overlap between risk
      management/insurance and actuarial science in terms of both required knowledge and career options. Schools that
      have earned a designation from the Society of Actuaries as a “College of Actuarial Excellence” demonstrate an
      overall commitment to finance, risk, and insurance education.</li>
