  <div class="card border border-dark" style="width: 100rem;">
    <h3 class="name text-center">3. Illinois State University - Normal, IL</h3>
    <p class="description">Illinois State University’s two degree tracks in insurance provide students with the
      opportunity to choose between multiple professional specializations in this already highly specialized field. The
      most general option is ISU’s standard bachelor of insurance and risk management degree program, which consists of
      a suite of business and insurance courses that span health, property, liability, risk management, financial
      planning, and more. Alternatively, more technologically adept students can opt for a specialization in Business
      Information Systems. This option places greater emphasis on programming skills and system analysis/design while
      still developing an in-depth understanding of insurance financial services.</p>
    <p>Annual Net Price: $17,509</p>
    <p>Score: 78.0</p>
  </div>
  </div>

</section>
<section class="flex-container card-flex" style="margin:35px;">
  <div class="card border border-dark" style="width: 100rem;">
    <h3 class="name text-center">4. Olivet College - Olivet, MI</h3>
    <p class="description">Olivet College is one of the few schools with an RMI curriculum so robust that it offers its
      own set of specializations. This means that students will not only acquire a solid understanding of their chosen
      field, but they’ll also customize their education through a “special interest track” in “Agency” or “Insurer.”
      Beyond this, Olivet’s top insurance and risk management major receives plenty of support from its on-campus
      chapter of Gamma Iota Sigma. Indeed, GIS plays a significant role in the RMI degree program, offering a wide
      range of co-curricular activities and opportunities to augment the comprehensive business, insurance, and finance
      core curriculum.</p>
    <p>Annual Net Price: $21,449</p>
    <p>Score: 72.0</p>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="flex-container card-flex" style="margin:35px;">
  <div class="card border border-dark" style="width: 100rem;">
    <h3 class="name text-center">5. Florida State University - Tallahassee, FL</h3>
    <p class="description">Currently ranked among U.S. News’ best business programs nationwide, Florida State
      University’s affordable insurance and risk management studies program already receives plenty of attention – and
      for good reason. Some of the program’s biggest highlights are its excellent graduate job placement rates and
      ample internship and scholarship opportunities—but that’s only the beginning. After all, FSU didn’t stumble upon
      these impressive statistics just by luck; rather, they are the result of a concerted departmental effort to help
      students network and find interviews. In addition to the career center’s targeted professional training services,
      RMI majors can also make connections through a special two-day job fair and placement program known as “Insurance
      Days.”</p>
    <p>Annual Net Price: $16,708</p>
    <p>Score: 71.0</p>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="flex-container card-flex" style="margin:35px;">
  <div class="card border border-dark" style="width: 100rem;">
    <h3 class="name text-center">6. University of Central Arkansas - Conway, AR</h3>
    <p class="description">Currently, the University of Central Arkansas is the only place in the state to find an
      accredited bachelor’s degree in risk management and insurance. And while this admittedly makes UCA’s the best
      program in Arkansas by default, its high-value package of coursework and extracurriculars would perform just as
      well in a much more competitive arena. Among the most notable benefits are an optional Financial Planning Track
      within the major, an on-campus chapter of Gamma Iota Sigma, and an opportunity to earn a Chartered Property
      Casualty Underwriter (CPCU) Certificate prior to graduating. RMI majors also have access to unique resources –
      including a Student Resume Book – through the university’s Center for Insurance & Risk Management Studies.</p>
    <p>Annual Net Price: $12,798</p>
    <p>Score: 67.0</p>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="flex-container card-flex" style="margin:35px;">
  <div class="card border border-dark" style="width: 100rem;">
    <h3 class="name text-center">7. Ball State University - Muncie, IN</h3>
    <p class="description">With an average net price of less than $13,000, Ball State University easily qualifies as
      one of the most affordable bachelor of insurance and risk management degree programs in the country. But a cheap
      degree is hardly all Ball State has to offer. In fact, the school provides an impressively comprehensive survey
      of the field, thanks to a curriculum that emphasizes best practices and a faculty with plenty of industry
      experience. What’s more, BSU houses a dedicated Center for Actuarial Science, Insurance, and Risk Management that
      not only provides coursework, but also conducts actuarial research, runs professional-in-residence programs, and
      offers scholarship and internship opportunities for undergraduates.</p>
    <p>Annual Net Price: $$12,847</p>
    <p>Score: 64.0</p>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="flex-container card-flex" style="margin:35px;">
  <div class="card border border-dark" style="width: 100rem;">
    <h3 class="name text-center">9. Eastern Kentucky University - Richmond, KY</h3>
    <p class="description">Like Utica, Eastern Kentucky University provides two pathways as part of its affordable
      undergraduate risk management programs: a BBA degree and a BS degree in Risk Management and Insurance. The
      differences between the two options are not dramatic – but they’re not entirely cosmetic, either. Most
      significantly, the BBA requires a dedicated business-driven core curriculum, whereas the BS program incorporates
      a more generalized elective schedule. And since EKU is the only school in the state that even offers an undergrad
      RMI program, the fact that it offers two choices just makes the experience that much better for local students
      hoping to enter the field.</p>
    <p>Annual Net Price: $21,740</p>
    <p>Score: 62.0</p>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="flex-container card-flex" style="margin:35px;">
  <div class="card border border-dark" style="width: 100rem;">
    <h3 class="name text-center">10. Utica College - Utica, NY</h3>
    <p class="description">At Utica College, students have two options for earning an affordable bachelor’s degree in
      risk management and insurance. The first and oldest of the two is a management degree with a concentration in
      risk management, which enabled Utica to take the first steps in developing a comprehensive curriculum when RMI
      programs were still exceedingly rare (even today there are only about 60 nationwide). The second and newer of the
      two is a dedicated BS in Risk Management and Insurance, which launched with a full suite of relevant classes –
      and even offers separate concentrations in Insurance and Risk Management.</p>
    <p>Annual Net Price: $22,466</p>
    <p>Score: 59.0</p>
  </div>
</section>